<BODY>
<DIV1 N="2" TYPE="volume">
<PB REF="026108_0067_0FCFAE6C4E518700">
<HEAD>THE INQUISITOR, &amp;c.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>EAST INDIAN CONTINUED.</HEAD>
<P>POOR fellow! said I, looking at him with an eye of compassion as he went out of the apartment&mdash;Poor fellow! thou hast been hardly used by one man who called himself a Christian, and it makes thee suspect the whole race&mdash;But, surely, said I, it is not a man's barely professing Christianity that makes him worthy that character; a man must behave with humanity, not only to his fellow-creatures, but to the animal creation, before he can be ranked with propriety among that exalted class of mortals.</P>
<P>The man who with unmerciful hand scourges his slave, does he then remember that the person he is chastising is endowed with the same sense of feeling as himself, and is as sensible of pain, hunger, thirst, cold, aye, and all the social blessings of life? has filial, conjugal, and paternal affection?&mdash;then why, because he is a slave, should you bestow on him pain|ful stripes, when yourself would shrink to receive but the smallest of them&mdash;Does the name of Slave,&mdash;</P>
<P>Slave! said I, rising as I spoke, while the san|guine tide that plays about my heart rushed unbidden to my cheeks&mdash;</P>
<P>Why did I blush, why did I tremble, as I pro|nounced the word slave?&mdash;It was because I was <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of the appellation&mdash;It is a word that should never be used between man and man&mdash;The negro <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 words"> burning sand, of Africa was born as free as
<PB N="72" REF="026108_0068_0FCFAE6AA981F230">
him who draws his first breath in Britain&mdash;and shall a Christian, a man whose mind is enlightened by education and religion, for a little sordid pelf, sell the freedom of this poor negro, only because he differs from him in complex<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">&mdash;what right has an Eu|ropean to sell an <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> do they leave their na|tive land and see<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> our <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> by arts entice our coun|trymen away, and make them slaves?&mdash;</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>THE SLAVE.</HEAD>
<P>I WALKED out and endeavoured to dissipate the disagreeable reflection; but the idea, of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">avery pur|sued me still.</P>
<P>Unhappy man, said I, as busy fancy drew out the sad scene.</P>
<P>She held up to my mind's eye a man born to a good inheritance, and surrounded with all the comforts, all the blessings, he desired&mdash;but he was a negro.</P>
<P>He was sitting in his little hut, his jetty compa|nion by his side; one infant at her breast, two others prattling at her knee; she looked, she felt happy. Her husband, her children, were with her; serenity played on every countenance; content had fixed her habitation in their dwelling&mdash;Some Europeans en|ter&mdash;they deck his beloved children with baubles&mdash;they tie beads round the arms of his wife&mdash;and or|nament her jetty locks with glittering toys&mdash;He is charmed with their courtesy&mdash;He walks with them to the sea side, and takes his boy, his eldest darling, with him&mdash;they invite them on board the vessel&mdash;Poor soul! unsuspecting their treachery, he <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, and bids adieu to liberty for ever&mdash;His wife, taking advantage of his absence, trims up their but&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> her dear babes to sleep&mdash;and then prepares a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">|per for her love, composed of wholesome roots and fruit&mdash;She wonders why he stays&mdash;She leaves h<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">r
<PB N="73" REF="026108_0069_0FCFAE6917A77350">
home and walks toward the sea, she sees him embark&mdash;her child goes too&mdash;the sailors spread the sails&mdash;the vessel moves&mdash;she shrieks&mdash;but there my heart was wrung so keenly, I could go no farther.</P>
<P>I left the wife, and followed the poor negro&mdash;he had no comfort but the idea that he should be with his child; that he should have it in his power to ease him if heavy tasks were imposed, to guard him from dangers and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">each him to be resigned and content|ed.&mdash;They arrive at Barbadoes&mdash;they are exposed to sale and allotted to different masters.</P>
<P>Alas! poor man, tears and intreaties are vain; you are in <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> of the sons of Mammon.</P>
<P>Fancy still led me forward&mdash;I saw him when age and infirmities came on without one comfort, with|out one friend, on a miserable bed, sickness and sad remembrance his only companions&mdash;he is wea|ry of life&mdash;he offers up a prayer for his still dear companion, for his children, his hapless enslaved child&mdash;He dies&mdash;and is thrown into the grave without a prayer to consecrate the ground, without one tear of affection or regret being shed upon his bier</P>
<P>Had not that poor negro a soul?</P>
<P>Yes&mdash;and in futurity it shall appear white and spotless at the throne of Grace, to confound the man who called himself a Christian, and yet betrayed a fellow-creature into bondage.</P>
<P>It would give me a great deal of pleasure, said I, to have the history of the East Indian&mdash;but when I have got it, how shall I translate it&mdash;I know nothing of the language; but, perhaps I may be able to pro|cure a person to translate it for me.</P>
<P>How do you do? my good friend, said a man, rather shabbily dressed.&mdash;Now I make it a rule ne|ver to turn my back on a man because he had rather wear a thread bare coat than run in debt with his tay|lor; so I turned about to present my hand to the
<PB N="74" REF="026108_0070_0FCF8CFA000B5270">
person who addressed me wish such cordiality, and perceived in him the features of an old school fellow.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>THE CLERGYMAN.</HEAD>
<P>I FEAR, said I, as we went forward&mdash;I fear you have not been successful in gaining any permanent settlement&mdash;pray how have you disposed of yourself these last seven years?</P>
<P>I have, he replied, been strangely tossed about, be|held various scenes, tried many different plans, and been unsuccessful in all.</P>
