<DIV2 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>SADI AND ZELIA.</HEAD>
<P>SADI, the son of Mahadan, the rich possessor of a fertile valley, watered by a beautiful river&mdash;who had slaves at his command, and was called by the sons of the East, Sadi the Happy.&mdash;Ah! what avails possessions and treasure?&mdash;and what is terrestrial hap|piness to man?&mdash;It vanisheth like a dream&mdash;it de|parteth like the mist of the morning before the beams of the sun.</P>
<P>Sadi, the once rich and happy, is a slave and wretched.&mdash;Go tell this to the daughters of joy&mdash;sound it in the ears of the sons of pleasure; for pros|perity has hardened their hearts&punc; and made them cal|lous to the feelings of humanity.</P>
<P>Zelia was the fairest among the daughters of Ara|bia; she was <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">ll, and straight as the pine tree; stately as the young cedar; her skin was like the ripe olive; her eyes, bright stars; her locks were like the polished <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">; and her teeth, fair rows of pearl; her lips were the colour of the ruby; and her breath like the breezes blowing from the spicy islands.</P>
<P>I built a bower for my Zelia; I adorned it with beautiful flowers, and planted sweet smelling shrubs around it.</P>
<P>With lofty trees I fenced out the sun beams <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the birds dwelt in their branches.&mdash;In the recess was a silver stream; the osiers and wild flowers hung <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> on its banks, and the swans sported on its bosom.</P>
<P>I sought my love among the daughters of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">
<PB N="103" REF="026108_0099_0FCFAF8258256580">
plain&mdash;I wooed her in the shady places&mdash;I brought her to the bower I had planted&mdash;I culled for her the choicest fruits&mdash;I brought her silks from the looms of Persia&mdash;I platted her hair with fresh flowers&mdash;I put costly jewels in her ears&mdash;and with pearls made bracelets for her arms.</P>
<P>We were the happiest among the happy; in the morning we arose together and worshipped the bright luminary of day.&mdash;We strayed over the fertile valleys&mdash;we sported with the young fawns; or re|tired from the heat, and reposed in the thick shade.</P>
<P>If I was in pain, she would sooth me.&mdash;I listened to her angel voice all day; and at night I reposed on her bosom.</P>
<P>The curtain of night had fallen over us&mdash;the stars shot their beams through the Heavens&mdash;the voice of distress met our ears&mdash;the plaints of sorrow invaded our dwelling&mdash;we went forth from the bower&mdash;we saw a Christian overpowered by his adversary. The blood issued from his bosom&mdash;his face was the picture of terror.</P>
<P>We bore him to our peaceful bower&mdash;we poured oil upon his wounds, and Zelia bound them up with her hands.&mdash;She watched him with the care of a sister&mdash;she gave him a part of our fruits, and brought him milk from the young camels.&mdash;He was grate|ful for the kindness we shewed&mdash;he swore by his God it should not be forgotten.&mdash;But, the word of a man is like unto the wind; it maketh a sound, pas|seth, and is no more remembered.</P>
<P>He left our bower once at early dawn&mdash;he tarri|ed till the close of evening.</P>
<P>Zelia had retired to rest&mdash;the moon beams played <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> her face&mdash;I contemplated her sleeping beams <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">.</P>
<P>The Christian I had saved, entered the bower&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> with him <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> ruffians.&mdash;
<PB N="104" REF="026108_0100_0FCFAF80EE3D91F8">
He seized upon my lovely Zelia&mdash;he listened not un|to her cries&mdash;he put a chain upon her feet, and bound the hands which had healed his wounds.</P>
<P>They took our costly ornaments and pearls&mdash;they bound me with an heavy iron chain, and led us like two slaves towards the sea.&mdash;They put us on board a ship he had prepared&mdash;they spread the sails&mdash;the wind blew from the shore, and in the morn are saw the main before us.</P>
<P>They took the chains from off my hands and feet&mdash;they gave me food, but pa<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">ed me from Zelia.</P>
<P>I heard her list up a voice of terror&mdash;I heard her call on Sadi for assistance&mdash;I rushed into the room where they confined her&mdash;I saw her in the embraces of a villain&mdash;I snatched a poniard from his side&mdash;I <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ade him instantly forego his prey.</P>
<P>Zelia like lightning darted from his arms&mdash;she cried, Now, Sadi!&mdash;Sadi, follow me!&mdash;then, from the window sprang into the ocean.</P>
<P>I sent the poniard to the traitor's heart.&mdash;I felt its warm blood gush upon my hand; then hastily obey|ed my charming Zelia.&mdash;I called her as I plunged into the sea&mdash;I sought my Zelia in the world of wa|ters; but the spirits of blessed saints had seen her virtue&mdash;they caught the lovely victim as she fell, and bore her on their wings to paradise.&mdash;I called for death to take a wretched life&mdash;I sought the friend of misery, but he fled from me.</P>
<P>Some other Christians saved me from the sea<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> they gave me food, and treated me with kindness&mdash;but the kindness of a Christian is like the song of the Syren, it sooths the senses, gains upon the heart then, unsuspected leads to destruction.&mdash;They <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> me with them to the Western world&mdash;they sold <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> wretched Sadi for a slave.</P>
<P>My haughty spirit was not used to bondage.&mdash;heard that England was the land of freedom&mdash;I <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">
<PB N="105" REF="026108_0101_0FCF8D50C8915C00">
myself on board an English ship, and sailed unseen into the boundless main.&mdash;I left my hiding p<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ace, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the captain, and bowed my face toward the d<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">k, before him.</P>
<P>He told me, I no more should be a slave&mdash;he brought me with him to this land of freedom.</P>
<P>But, here I found I also deceived; for, here mankind are slaves to vice, to avarice, to luxury, and to folly.&mdash;The man who brought me from the Wes|tern world, demanded payment for my passage over. Alas! I had been rifled by the Christians.&mdash;I had nought to give but grateful thanks and prayers.&mdash;He who had said I should not be a slave, confined me in a loathsome prison house&mdash;this was my wel|come to the land of freedom.</P>
<P>For seven long years I never felt the air, nor ever saw the chearful face of Heaven&mdash;but the angel of death that visits all the earth, then stopped the breath of my hard persecutor. I then was freed from out the loathsome prison, and for a moment I rejoiced in liberty; but soon I felt the gnawing pangs of hun|ger. I had no friend whose pity might relieve me&mdash;the spacious city was to me a desert, and I was starving in the land of plenty.&mdash;But, who can bear the griping hand of famine; who can sink under it and not complain? I laid me down upon the damp, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">old ground&mdash;I groaned aloud, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ore my hair through anguish; but many passed by, nor once re|garded me; and others scoffed and called me an im|postor. I thought the end of all my woes was come&mdash;I ceased to groan, and waited death's approach; but pity had not wholly fled the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> she dwells within the hearts of Christian women&mdash;one brought <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> something to allay my hunger; another put <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> money in my hand.&mdash;One seeming <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> wretched as myself, looked at me, shook her head, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> tears. I felt her kindness more than
<PB N="106" REF="026108_0102_0FCFAF7F65039600">
those before&mdash;the tear of pity healed my blessing heart.</P>
<P>But, the woes of Sadi soon will have an <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> soon shall I sleep, and be at rest for ever, for the sorrows of my heart overpower me, and pain and sickness bow me to the earth.&mdash;The lamp of life is very near exhausted; and when each night I lay me down to rest, I think not to behold another morning.</P>
<P>And what, alas! has wretched Sadi <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> and, who reduced him to this state of misery? Go tell the tale to all the Eastern world&mdash;Go warn them to be|ware of trusting Christians; for Sadi saved one from the jaws of death, and thus was his humanity re|warded.</P>
