<P>I am so situated, Sir, she replied, that I am una|voidably obliged to pass many hours entirely by my|self&mdash;In the former part of my life I have been en|gaged in many scenes, the remembrance of which, in these solitary hours, would be extremely painful, were it not for the relaxation and amusement I find in the exercise of my pen&mdash;I have but few acquaint|ance, she continued, and even those few might, by too frequent visits, grow tired of my company. I seldom go out but I meet with some object to en|gage my attention; and often when reflecting on the various scenes around me, I fall into a train of ideas which I feel a sort of pleasure in committing to paper; and in general they serve to occupy the next leisure or solitary hour.</P>
